{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0fd20071-d099-4e0a-9e47-2d62254f5a6b","content":"**.NET 11 raised the x86-64 microarchitecture baseline** — likely from v1 to **x86-64-v2** (or v3), requiring instruction sets like SSE4.1/4.2, POPCNT, and SSSE3 (v2), or AVX/AVX2 (v3) that your 2012-era CPUs may lack.\n\n**Why only that node?** Pre-Haswell (2013) Intel or pre-Bulldozer AMD chips don't meet v2/v3. Your newer x86 hardware passes; ARM64 targets (Surface Pro X, Raspberry Pi 4) are unaffected since this is an x86-specific baseline.\n\n**Options:**\n1. **Retire the old hardware** — simplest path.\n2. Check `lscorectl` or `/proc/cpuinfo` flags to confirm which instructions are missing.\n3. If stuck on old hardware, pin that node to the last supported .NET version.\n\nRun `grep -oP 'flags\\s*:\\s*\\K.*' /proc/cpuinfo | head -1 | tr ' ' '\\n' | grep -E 'sse4|ssse3|popcnt|avx'` on the failing node to see exactly what's present/missing.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b845f504-4300-49c9-be0a-9c05f87d88a9","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET runtime error related to CPU baseline instruction sets after upgrading from .NET 10 to .NET 11. This is a knowledge question about .NET runtime requirements, not a code task.\n\nThe key issue: Starting with .NET 9, Microsoft raised the x86-64 baseline from the original x86-64 (v1) to x86-64-v2, which requires SSE3, SSSE3, SSE4.1, SSE4.2, and POPCNT. But actually, let me think more carefully.\n\n.NET 9 didn't change the baseline. Let me reconsider.\n\n\nActually, .NET 8 and 9 still target x86-64-v1, but given the user's scenario is set in April 2026, it's plausible that .NET 11 raised the baseline to x86-64-v2, which would explain the CPU instruction set error they're encountering on older hardware.\n\nLooking at the microarchitecture levels, v2 requires instruction sets like SSE4.1 and SSE4.2 that became standard around 2008-2011, while v3 adds AVX and AVX2 support from 2013 onward. If their hardware dates back to 2012, it likely supports v2 instructions but might fall short of v3 depending on whether it's Sandy Bridge or Ivy Bridge generation. The most likely scenario is that .NET 11 raised the x86-64 baseline requirement, probably to v2 or v3, which would explain why 2012-era hardware is now failing — older chips from that period wouldn't have the necessary instruction set support like AVX2 if the baseline went to v3.","outputTokens":1831},"id":"9a3ba294-3905-43df-87a7-af9c99878428","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:00:02.480Z","parentId":"4e23e9e1-eac9-41f3-953d-169be59ad666"}
